_refine_special_details          
;
The structure exhibits pseudo-translation along the b-axis direction. 
Exact translational symmetry is broken by modulation of the lead iodide 
layer and by the positions of the ammonium and ethylene groups of the 
cations, which are modulated along b. 

The structure was refined as a 4-component twin including pseudo-
merohedral twinning (emulating monoclinic symmetry) and inversion 
twinning. Application of the twin transformation matrix 
-1 0 0 0 1 0 0 -0.5 -1 combined with inversion twinning resulted in 
BASF values of 0.01(2) (rotated around b-axis, not inverted), 0.13(2) 
(original domain inverted) and 0.02(2) (rotated around b-axis and 
inverted). 

The lead iodide part of the lattice was refined as disordered, with 
lead and iodide atoms approximately located in the pseudo-translated 
positions. The two moieties are related by non-crystallographic 
inversion symmetry (pseudo-inversion centers located halfway between 
major and minor moiety lead ions. The disorder emulates four-fold 
symmetry along b for the Pb-I lattice if occupancy rates would be equal. 
ADPs of major and minor disordered iodine atoms were restrained to be 
similar (SIMU 0.004 restraint with a distance cutoff of 2.1 Angstrom, 
thus only applied between pairs I atoms of the major and minor moiety, 
but not between atoms within the same moiety. The observed disorder 
necessarily creates similar disorder for the ammonium cations of the 
cations. Positions for the minor moiety N atoms were however not 
resolved and the disorder was omitted for the cations. Subject to these 
conditions the occupancy ratio refined to 0.9424(12) to 0.0576(12). 

Cations are related by pseudo-translation along b (and less so by 
pseudo-monoclinic symmetry) with only the ammonium and ethylene 
fragments not related by exact translation, resulting in substantial 
correlation between atom positions and ADPs of C and S atoms. 
To control correlation all cations were restrained to have similar 
geometries (SAME command of Shelxl) and Uij components of ADPs of all 
C, N and S atoms closer to each other than 2.0 Angstrom were restrained 
to be similar (SIMU 0.02 command of Shelxl). The outer thiophene rings 
showed signs of rotational disorder (negative residual density and 
large ADPs at S atoms, small ADPs and positive residual density at 
atoms C8). They were refined as two-fold disordered by rotation around 
C6-C7. The major and minor disordered moieties of each cation were each 
restrained to have similar geometries. The minor moiety thiophene units 
were restrained to be flat. 
Subject to these conditions the occupancy ratios refined to 0.74(2) to 
0.26(2) (moieties A/I), to 0.65(2) to 0.35(2) (moieties B/J), to 0.82(2)  
0.18(2) (moieties C/K), to 0.72(2) to 0.28(2) (moieties D/L), to 0.880(17) 
to 0.120(17) (moieties E/M), to 0.799(19) to 0.201(19 (moieties F/N), to 
0.862(18) to 0.138(18) (moieties G/O), and to 0.864(14) to 0.136(14) 
(moieties H/P).
;
